codebase.summary: The base path used to resolve relative URIs specified by classid, data, or archive. If not specified, the default is the base URI of the current document.

codetype.name: codetype
codetype.summary: The content type of the data specified by classid.

data.name: data
data.summary: The address of the resource as a valid URL. At least one of data and type must be defined.

declare.name: declare
declare.summary: The presence of this Boolean attribute makes this element a declaration only. The object must be instantiated by a subsequent `<object>` element. In HTML5, repeat the <object> element completely each time that the resource is reused.

form.name: form
form.summary: The form element, if any, that the object element is associated with (its form owner). The value of the attribute must be an ID of a form element in the same document.

height.name: height
height.summary: The height of the displayed resource, in CSS pixels. -- (Absolute values only. NO percentages)

name.name: name
name.summary: The name of valid browsing context (HTML5), or the name of the control (HTML 4).

standby.name: standby
standby.summary: A message that the browser can show while loading the object's implementation and data.

type.name: type
type.summary: The content type of the resource specified by data. At least one of data and type must be defined.

usemap.name: usemap
usemap.summary: A hash-name reference to a map element; that is a '#' followed by the value of a name of a map element.

width.name: width
width.summary: The width of the display resource, in CSS pixels. -- (Absolute values only. NO percentages)

html/ol.name: ol
html/ol.summary: The `<ol>` HTML element represents an ordered list of items — typically rendered as a numbered list.

reversed.name: reversed
reversed.summary: This Boolean attribute specifies that the list's items are in reverse order. Items will be numbered from high to low.

start.name: start
start.summary: An integer to start counting from for the list items. Always an Arabic numeral (1, 2, 3, etc.), even when the numbering `type` is letters or Roman numerals. For example, to start numbering elements from the letter "d" or the Roman numeral "iv," use `start="4"`.

html/optgroup.name: optgroup
html/optgroup.summary: The `<optgroup>` HTML element creates a grouping of options within a select element.

disabled.name: disabled
disabled.summary: If this Boolean attribute is set, none of the items in this option group is selectable. Often browsers grey out such control and it won't receive any browsing events, like mouse clicks or focus-related ones.

label.name: label
label.summary: The name of the group of options, which the browser can use when labeling the options in the user interface. This attribute is mandatory if this element is used.

html/option.name: option
html/option.summary: The `<option>` HTML element is used to define an item contained in a select, an optgroup, or a datalist element. As such, `<option>` can represent menu items in popups and other lists of items in an HTML document.

disabled.name: disabled
disabled.summary: If this Boolean attribute is set, this option is not checkable. Often browsers grey out such control and it won't receive any browsing event, like mouse clicks or focus-related ones. If this attribute is not set, the element can still be disabled if one of its ancestors is a disabled optgroup element.

label.name: label
label.summary: This attribute is text for the label indicating the meaning of the option. If the `label` attribute isn't defined, its value is that of the element text content.

selected.name: selected
selected.summary: If present, this Boolean attribute indicates that the option is initially selected. If the `<option>` element is the descendant of a select element whose multiple attribute is not set, only one single `<option>` of this select element may have the `selected` attribute.

value.name: value
value.summary: The content of this attribute represents the value to be submitted with the form, should this option be selected. If this attribute is omitted, the value is taken from the text content of the option element.

html/output.name: output
html/output.summary: The `<output>` HTML element is a container element into which a site or app can inject the results of a calculation or the outcome of a user action.

for.name: for
for.summary: A space-separated list of other elements' ids, indicating that those elements contributed input values to (or otherwise affected) the calculation.

form.name: form
form.summary: The form element to associate the output with (its form owner). The value of this attribute must be the id of a `<form>` in the same document. (If this attribute is not set, the `<output>` is associated with its ancestor `<form>` element, if any.)

name.name: name
name.summary: The element's name. Used in the HTMLFormElement.elements API.

html/p.name: p
html/p.summary:
The `

` HTML element represents a paragraph. Paragraphs are usually represented in visual media as blocks of text separated from adjacent blocks by blank lines and/or first-line indentation, but HTML paragraphs can be any structural grouping of related content, such as images or form fields.

html/param.name: param
html/param.summary: The `<param>` HTML element defines parameters for an object element.

value.name: value
value.summary: Specifies the value of the parameter.

type.name: type
type.summary: Only used if the `valuetype` is set to `ref`. Specifies the MIME type of values found at the URI specified by value.

valuetype.name: valuetype
valuetype.summary: Specifies the type of the `value` attribute. Possible values are.

html/picture.name: picture
html/picture.summary: The `<picture>` HTML element contains zero or more source elements and one img element to offer alternative versions of an image for different display/device scenarios.

html/plaintext.name: plaintext
html/plaintext.summary: The `<plaintext>` HTML element renders everything following the start tag as raw text, ignoring any following HTML. There is no closing tag, since everything after it is considered raw text.

html/portal.name: portal
html/portal.summary: The `<portal>` HTML element enables the embedding of another HTML page into the current one for the purposes of allowing smoother navigation into new pages.

referrerpolicy.name: referrerpolicy
referrerpolicy.summary: Sets the referrer policy to use when requesting the page at the URL given as the value of the `src` attribute.

src.name: src
src.summary: The URL of the page to embed.

html/pre.name: pre
html/pre.summary: The `<pre>` HTML element represents preformatted text which is to be presented exactly as written in the HTML file. The text is typically rendered using a non-proportional, or monospaced, font. Whitespace inside this element is displayed as written.

cols.name: cols
cols.summary: Contains the preferred count of characters that a line should have. It was a non-standard synonym of width. To achieve such an effect, use CSS width instead.

width.name: width
width.summary: Contains the preferred count of characters that a line should have. Though technically still implemented, this attribute has no visual effect; to achieve such an effect, use CSS width instead.

wrap.name: wrap
wrap.summary: Is a hint indicating how the overflow must happen. In modern browser this hint is ignored and no visual effect results in its present; to achieve such an effect, use CSS white-space instead.

html/progress.name: progress
html/progress.summary: The `<progress>` HTML element displays an indicator showing the completion progress of a task, typically displayed as a progress bar.

html/q.name: q
html/q.summary: The `<q>` HTML element indicates that the enclosed text is a short inline quotation. Most modern browsers implement this by surrounding the text in quotation marks. This element is intended for short quotations that don't require paragraph breaks; for long quotations use the blockquote element.

cite.name: cite
cite.summary: The value of this attribute is a URL that designates a source document or message for the information quoted. This attribute is intended to point to information explaining the context or the reference for the quote.

html/rb.name: rb
html/rb.summary: The `<rb>` HTML element is used to delimit the base text component of a ruby annotation, i.e. the text that is being annotated. One `<rb>` element should wrap each separate atomic segment of the base text.

html/rp.name: rp
html/rp.summary: The `<rp>` HTML element is used to provide fall-back parentheses for browsers that do not support display of ruby annotations using the ruby element. One `<rp>` element should enclose each of the opening and closing parentheses that wrap the rt element that contains the annotation's text.

html/rt.name: rt
html/rt.summary: The `<rt>` HTML element specifies the ruby text component of a ruby annotation, which is used to provide pronunciation, translation, or transliteration information for East Asian typography. The `<rt>` element must always be contained within a ruby element.

html/rtc.name: rtc
html/rtc.summary: The `<rtc>` HTML element embraces semantic annotations of characters presented in a ruby of rb elements used inside of ruby element. rb elements can have both pronunciation (rt) and semantic (rtc) annotations.

html/ruby.name: ruby
html/ruby.summary: The `<ruby>` HTML element represents small annotations that are rendered above, below, or next to base text, usually used for showing the pronunciation of East Asian characters. It can also be used for annotating other kinds of text, but this usage is less common.

html/s.name: s
html/s.summary: The `<s>` HTML element renders text with a strikethrough, or a line through it. Use the `<s>` element to represent things that are no longer relevant or no longer accurate. However, `<s>` is not appropriate when indicating document edits; for that, use the del and ins elements, as appropriate.

html/samp.name: samp
html/samp.summary: The `<samp>` HTML element is used to enclose inline text which represents sample (or quoted) output from a computer program. Its contents are typically rendered using the browser's default monospaced font (such as wikipedia or Lucida Console).

html/script.name: script
html/script.summary: The `<script>` HTML element is used to embed executable code or data; this is typically used to embed or refer to JavaScript code. The `<script>` element can also be used with other languages, such as WebGL's GLSL shader programming language and JSON.

async.name: async
async.summary: For classic scripts, if the `async` attribute is present, then the classic script will be fetched in parallel to parsing and evaluated as soon as it is available.

crossorigin.name: crossorigin
crossorigin.summary: Normal `script` elements pass minimal information to the  for scripts which do not pass the standard CORS checks. To allow error logging for sites which use a separate domain for static media, use this attribute. See CORS settings attributes for a more descriptive explanation of its valid arguments.

defer.name: defer
defer.summary: This Boolean attribute is set to indicate to a browser that the script is meant to be executed after the document has been parsed, but before firing Document/DOMContentLoaded_event.

fetchpriority.name: fetchpriority
fetchpriority.summary: Provides a hint of the relative priority to use when fetching an external script

integrity.name: integrity
integrity.summary: This attribute contains inline metadata that a user agent can use to verify that a fetched resource has been delivered free of unexpected manipulation. See Subresource Integrity.

nomodule.name: nomodule
nomodule.summary: This Boolean attribute is set to indicate that the script should not be executed in browsers that support ES2015 modules — in effect, this can be used to serve fallback scripts to older browsers that do not support modular JavaScript code.

nonce.name: nonce
nonce.summary: A cryptographic nonce (number used once) to allow scripts in a script-src Content-Security-Policy. The server must generate a unique nonce value each time it transmits a policy. It is critical to provide a nonce that cannot be guessed as bypassing a resource's policy is otherwise trivial.

referrerpolicy.name: referrerpolicy
referrerpolicy.summary: Indicates which referrer to send when fetching the script, or resources fetched by the script.

src.name: src
src.summary: This attribute specifies the URI of an external script; this can be used as an alternative to embedding a script directly within a document.

type.name: type
type.summary: This attribute indicates the type of script represented. The value of this attribute will be in one of the following categories.

html/section.name: section
html/section.summary: The `<section>` HTML element represents a generic standalone section of a document, which doesn't have a more specific semantic element to represent it. Sections should always have a heading, with very few exceptions.

html/select.name: select
html/select.summary: The `<select>` HTML element represents a control that provides a menu of options.

autocomplete.name: autocomplete
autocomplete.summary: A string providing a hint for a user agent autocomplete feature. See The HTML autocomplete attribute for a complete list of values and details on how to use autocomplete.

autofocus.name: autofocus
autofocus.summary: This Boolean attribute lets you specify that a form control should have input focus when the page loads. Only one form element in a document can have the `autofocus` attribute.

disabled.name: disabled
disabled.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates that the user cannot interact with the control. If this attribute is not specified, the control inherits its setting from the containing element, for example fieldset; if there is no containing element with the `disabled` attribute set, then the control is enabled.

form.name: form
form.summary: The form element to associate the `<select>` with (its form owner). The value of this attribute must be the id of a `<form>` in the same document. (If this attribute is not set, the `<select>` is associated with its ancestor `<form>` element, if any.)

multiple.name: multiple
multiple.summary: This Boolean attribute indicates that multiple options can be selected in the list. If it is not specified, then only one option can be selected at a time. When `multiple` is specified, most browsers will show a scrolling list box instead of a single line dropdown.

name.name: name
name.summary: This attribute is used to specify the name of the control.

required.name: required
required.summary: A Boolean attribute indicating that an option with a non-empty string value must be selected.

size.name: size
size.summary: If the control is presented as a scrolling list box (e.g. when `multiple` is specified), this attribute represents the number of rows in the list that should be visible at one time. Browsers are not required to present a select element as a scrolled list box. The default value is `0`.

html/shadow.name: shadow
html/shadow.summary: The `<shadow>` HTML element—an obsolete part of the Web Components technology suite—was intended to be used as a shadow DOM insertion point. You might have used it if you have created multiple shadow roots under a shadow host. It is not useful in ordinary HTML.

html/slot.name: slot
html/slot.summary: The `<slot>` HTML element—part of the Web Components technology suite—is a placeholder inside a web component that you can fill with your own markup, which lets you create separate DOM trees and present them together.

html/small.name: small
html/small.summary: The `<small>` HTML element represents side-comments and small print, like copyright and legal text, independent of its styled presentation. By default, it renders text within it one font-size smaller, such as from `small` to `x-small`.

html/source.name: source
html/source.summary: The `<source>` HTML element specifies multiple media resources for the picture, the audio element, or the video element. It is an empty element, meaning that it has no content and does not have a closing tag. It is commonly used to offer the same media content in multiple file formats in order to provide compatibility with a broad range of browsers given their differing support for image file formats and media file formats.

type.name: type
type.summary: The MIME media type of the resource, optionally with a `codecs` parameter.

src.name: src
src.summary: Required if the `source` element’s parent is an audio and video element, but not allowed if the `source` element’s parent is a picture element.

srcset.name: srcset
srcset.summary: Required if the `source` element’s parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` element’s parent is an audio or video element.

sizes.name: sizes
sizes.summary: Allowed if the `source` element’s parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` element’s parent is an audio or video element.

media.name: media
media.summary: Allowed if the `source` element’s parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` element’s parent is an audio or video element.

height.name: height
height.summary: Allowed if the `source` element’s parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` element’s parent is an audio or video element.

width.name: width
width.summary: Allowed if the `source` element’s parent is a picture element, but not allowed if the `source` element’s parent is an audio or video element.

html/spacer.name: spacer
html/spacer.summary: The `<spacer>` HTML element is an obsolete HTML element which allowed insertion of empty spaces on pages. It was devised by Netscape to accomplish the same effect as a single-pixel layout image, which was something web designers used to use to add white spaces to web pages without actually using an image. However, `<spacer>` no longer supported by any major browser and the same effects can now be achieved using simple CSS.

html/span.name: span
html/span.summary: The `<span>` HTML element is a generic inline container for phrasing content, which does not inherently represent anything. It can be used to group elements for styling purposes (using the class or id attributes), or because they share attribute values, such as lang. It should be used only when no other semantic element is appropriate. `<span>` is very much like a div element, but div is a block-level element whereas a `<span>` is an inline element.

html/strike.name: strike
html/strike.summary: The `<strike>` HTML element places a strikethrough (horizontal line) over text.

html/strong.name: strong
html/strong.summary: The `<strong>` HTML element indicates that its contents have strong importance, seriousness, or urgency. Browsers typically render the contents in bold type.

html/style.name: style
html/style.summary: The `<style>` HTML element contains style information for a document, or part of a document. It contains CSS, which is applied to the contents of the document containing the `<style>` element.

media.name: media
media.summary: This attribute defines which media the style should be applied to. Its value is a media query, which defaults to `all` if the attribute is missing.

nonce.name: nonce
nonce.summary: A cryptographic nonce (number used once) used to allow inline styles in a style-src Content-Security-Policy. The server must generate a unique nonce value each time it transmits a policy. It is critical to provide a nonce that cannot be guessed as bypassing a resource's policy is otherwise trivial.

title.name: title
title.summary: This attribute specifies alternative style sheet sets.

html/sub.name: sub
html/sub.summary: The `<sub>` HTML element specifies inline text which should be displayed as subscript for solely typographical reasons. Subscripts are typically rendered with a lowered baseline using smaller text.

html/summary.name: summary
html/summary.summary: The `<summary>` HTML element specifies a summary, caption, or legend for a details element's disclosure box. Clicking the `<summary>` element toggles the state of the parent `<details>` element open and closed.

html/sup.name: sup
html/sup.summary: The `<sup>` HTML element specifies inline text which is to be displayed as superscript for solely typographical reasons. Superscripts are usually rendered with a raised baseline using smaller text.

html/table.name: table
html/table.summary: The `<table>` HTML element represents tabular data — that is, information presented in a two-dimensional table comprised of rows and columns of cells containing data.

html/tbody.name: tbody
html/tbody.summary: The `<tbody>` HTML element encapsulates a set of table rows (tr elements), indicating that they comprise the body of the table (table).

html/td.name: td
html/td.summary: The `<td>` HTML element defines a cell of a table that contains data. It participates in the table model.

colspan.name: colspan
colspan.summary: This attribute contains a non-negative integer value that indicates for how many columns the cell extends. Its default value is `1`. Values higher than 1000 will be considered as incorrect and will be set to the default value (1).

headers.name: headers
headers.summary: This attribute contains a list of space-separated strings, each corresponding to the id attribute of the th elements that apply to this element.

rowspan.name: rowspan
rowspan.summary: This attribute contains a non-negative integer value that indicates for how many rows the cell extends. Its default value is `1`; if its value is set to `0`, it extends until the end of the table section (thead, tbody, tfoot, even if implicitly defined), that the cell belongs to. Values higher than 65534 are clipped down to 65534.

html/template.name: template
html/template.summary: The `<template>` HTML element is a mechanism for holding HTML that is not to be rendered immediately when a page is loaded but may be instantiated subsequently during runtime using JavaScript.

html/textarea.name: textarea
html/textarea.summary: The `<textarea>` HTML element represents a multi-line plain-text editing control, useful when you want to allow users to enter a sizeable amount of free-form text, for example a comment on a review or feedback form.

autocomplete.name: autocomplete
autocomplete.summary: This attribute indicates whether the value of the control can be automatically completed by the browser. Possible values are.

html/tfoot.name: tfoot
html/tfoot.summary: The `<tfoot>` HTML element defines a set of rows summarizing the columns of the table.

html/th.name: th
html/th.summary: The `<th>` HTML element defines a cell as header of a group of table cells. The exact nature of this group is defined by the scope and headers attributes.

abbr.name: abbr
abbr.summary: This attribute contains a short abbreviated description of the cell's content. Some user-agents, such as speech readers, may present this description before the content itself.

colspan.name: colspan
colspan.summary: This attribute contains a non-negative integer value that indicates for how many columns the cell extends. Its default value is `1`. Values higher than 1000 will be considered as incorrect and will be set to the default value (1).

headers.name: headers
headers.summary: This attribute contains a list of space-separated strings, each corresponding to the id attribute of the th elements that apply to this element.

rowspan.name: rowspan
rowspan.summary: This attribute contains a non-negative integer value that indicates for how many rows the cell extends. Its default value is `1`; if its value is set to `0`, it extends until the end of the table section (thead, tbody, tfoot, even if implicitly defined), that the cell belongs to. Values higher than 65534 are clipped down to 65534.

scope.name: scope
scope.summary: This enumerated attribute defines the cells that the header (defined in the th) element relates to

html/thead.name: thead
html/thead.summary: The `<thead>` HTML element defines a set of rows defining the head of the columns of the table.

html/time.name: time
html/time.summary: The `<time>` HTML element represents a specific period in time. It may include the `datetime` attribute to translate dates into machine-readable format, allowing for better search engine results or custom features such as reminders.

datetime.name: datetime
datetime.summary: This attribute indicates the time and/or date of the element and must be in one of the formats described below.

html/title.name: title
html/title.summary: The `<title>` HTML element defines the document's title that is shown in a Browser's title bar or a page's tab. It only contains text; tags within the element are ignored.

html/tr.name: tr
html/tr.summary: The `<tr>` HTML element defines a row of cells in a table. The row's cells can then be established using a mix of td (data cell) and th (header cell) elements.

html/track.name: track
html/track.summary: The `<track>` HTML element is used as a child of the media elements, audio and video. It lets you specify timed text tracks (or time-based data), for example to automatically handle subtitles. The tracks are formatted in WebVTT format (`.vtt` files) — Web Video Text Tracks.

default.name: default
default.summary: This attribute indicates that the track should be enabled unless the user's preferences indicate that another track is more appropriate. This may only be used on one `track` element per media element.

kind.name: kind
kind.summary: How the text track is meant to be used. If omitted the default kind is `subtitles`. If the attribute contains an invalid value, it will use `metadata` (Versions of Chrome earlier than 52 treated an invalid value as `subtitles`). The following keywords are allowed.

label.name: label
label.summary: A user-readable title of the text track which is used by the browser when listing available text tracks.

src.name: src
src.summary: Address of the track (`.vtt` file). Must be a valid URL. This attribute must be specified and its URL value must have the same origin as the document — unless the audio or video parent element of the `track` element has a `crossorigin` attribute.

srclang.name: srclang
srclang.summary: Language of the track text data. It must be a valid BCP 47 language tag. If the `kind` attribute is set to `subtitles`, then `srclang` must be defined.

html/tt.name: tt
html/tt.summary: The `<tt>` HTML element creates inline text which is presented using the user agent default monospace font face. This element was created for the purpose of rendering text as it would be displayed on a fixed-width display such as a teletype, text-only screen, or line printer.

html/u.name: u
html/u.summary: The `<u>` HTML element represents a span of inline text which should be rendered in a way that indicates that it has a non-textual annotation. This is rendered by default as a simple solid underline, but may be altered using CSS.

html/ul.name: ul
html/ul.summary: The `<ul>` HTML element represents an unordered list of items, typically rendered as a bulleted list.

html/var.name: var
html/var.summary: The `<var>` HTML element represents the name of a variable in a mathematical expression or a programming context. It's typically presented using an italicized version of the current typeface, although that behavior is browser-dependent.

html/video.name: video
html/video.summary: The `<video>` HTML element embeds a media player which supports video playback into the document. You can use `<video>` for audio content as well, but the audio element may provide a more appropriate user experience.

autoplay.name: autoplay
autoplay.summary: A Boolean attribute; if specified, the video automatically begins to play back as soon as it can do so without stopping to finish loading the data.

autopictureinpicture.name: autopictureinpicture
autopictureinpicture.summary: A Boolean attribute which if `true` indicates that the element should automatically toggle picture-in-picture mode when the user switches back and forth between this document and another document or application.

controls.name: controls
controls.summary: If this attribute is present, the browser will offer controls to allow the user to control video playback, including volume, seeking, and pause/resume playback.

controlslist.name: controlslist
controlslist.summary: The `controlslist` attribute, when specified, helps the browser select what controls to show on the media element whenever the browser shows its own set of controls (e.g. when the `controls` attribute is specified).

crossorigin.name: crossorigin
crossorigin.summary: This enumerated attribute indicates whether to use CORS to fetch the related video. CORS-enabled resources can be reused in the canvas element without being tainted. The allowed values are.

disablepictureinpicture.name: disablepictureinpicture
disablepictureinpicture.summary: Prevents the browser from suggesting a Picture-in-Picture context menu or to request Picture-in-Picture automatically in some cases.

disableremoteplayback.name: disableremoteplayback
disableremoteplayback.summary: A Boolean attribute used to disable the capability of remote playback in devices that are attached using wired (HDMI, DVI, etc.) and wireless technologies (Miracast, Chromecast, DLNA, AirPlay, etc).

height.name: height
height.summary: The height of the video's display area, in CSS pixels (absolute values only; no percentages.)

loop.name: loop
loop.summary: A Boolean attribute; if specified, the browser will automatically seek back to the start upon reaching the end of the video.

muted.name: muted
muted.summary: A Boolean attribute that indicates the default setting of the audio contained in the video. If set, the audio will be initially silenced. Its default value is `false`, meaning that the audio will be played when the video is played.

playsinline.name: playsinline
playsinline.summary: A Boolean attribute indicating that the video is to be played "inline", that is within the element's playback area. Note that the absence of this attribute does not imply that the video will always be played in fullscreen.

poster.name: poster
poster.summary: A URL for an image to be shown while the video is downloading. If this attribute isn't specified, nothing is displayed until the first frame is available, then the first frame is shown as the poster frame.

preload.name: preload
preload.summary: This enumerated attribute is intended to provide a hint to the browser about what the author thinks will lead to the best user experience with regards to what content is loaded before the video is played

src.name: src
src.summary: The URL of the video to embed. This is optional; you may instead use the source element within the video block to specify the video to embed.

width.name: width
width.summary: The width of the video's display area, in CSS pixels (absolute values only; no percentages).

html/wbr.name: wbr
html/wbr.summary: The `<wbr>` HTML element represents a word break opportunity—a position within text where the browser may optionally break a line, though its line-breaking rules would not otherwise create a break at that location.

html/xmp.name: xmp
html/xmp.summary: The `<xmp>` HTML element renders text between the start and end tags without interpreting the HTML in between and using a monospaced font. The HTML2 specification recommended that it should be rendered wide enough to allow 80 characters per line.

svg/*.name: SVG:*
svg/*.summary: Container to hold the global attributes of all SVG elements.

class.name: class
class.summary: Assigns a class name or set of class names to an element. You may assign the same class name or names to any number of elements, however, multiple class names must be separated by whitespace characters.

style.name: style
style.summary: The `style` attribute allows to style an element using CSS declarations. It functions identically to the `style` attribute in HTML.

id.name: id
id.summary: The `id` attribute assigns a unique name to an element.

lang.name: lang
lang.summary: The `lang` attribute specifies the primary language used in contents and attributes containing text content of particular elements.

tabindex.name: tabindex
tabindex.summary: The `tabindex` attribute allows you to control whether an element is focusable and to define the relative order of the element for the purposes of sequential focus navigation.

xml:base.name: xml:base
xml:base.summary: The `xml:base` attribute specifies a base IRI other than the base IRI of the document or external entity.

xml:lang.name: xml:lang
xml:lang.summary: The `xml:lang` attribute specifies the primary language used in contents and attributes containing text content of particular elements.

xml:space.name: xml:space
xml:space.summary: SVG supports the built-in XML `xml:space` attribute to handle whitespace characters inside elements. Child elements inside an element may also have an `xml:space` attribute that overrides the parent's one.

svg/a.name: a
svg/a.summary: The <a> SVG element creates a hyperlink to other web pages, files, locations in the same page, email addresses, or any other URL. It is very similar to HTML's a element.

href.name: href
href.summary: The `href` attribute defines a link to a resource as a reference URL. The exact meaning of that link depends on the context of each element using it.

target.name: target
target.summary: The `target` attribute should be used when there are multiple possible targets for the ending resource, such as when the parent document is embedded within an HTML or XHTML document, or is viewed with a tabbed browser. This attribute specifies the name of the browsing context (e.g., a browser tab or an (X)HTML iframe or object element) into which a document is to be opened when the link is activated.

xlink:href.name: xlink:href
xlink:href.summary: The `xlink:href` attribute defines a reference to a resource as a reference IRI. The exact meaning of that link depends on the context of each element using it.

svg/altGlyph.name: altGlyph
svg/altGlyph.summary: The `<altGlyph>` SVG element allows sophisticated selection of the glyphs used to render its child character data.

x.name: x
x.summary: The `x` attribute defines an x-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.

y.name: y
y.summary: The `y` attribute defines a y-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.

dx.name: dx
dx.summary: The `dx` attribute indicates a shift along the x-axis on the position of an element or its content.

dy.name: dy
dy.summary: The `dy` attribute indicates a shift along the y-axis on the position of an element or its content.

rotate.name: rotate
rotate.summary: The `rotate` attribute specifies how the animated element rotates as it travels along a path specified in an animateMotion element.

glyphRef.name: glyphRef
glyphRef.summary: The `glyphRef` attribute represents the glyph identifier, the format of which is dependent on the format of the given font.

format.name: format
format.summary: The `format` attribute indicates the format of the given font.

xlink:href.name: xlink:href
xlink:href.summary: The `xlink:href` attribute defines a reference to a resource as a reference IRI. The exact meaning of that link depends on the context of each element using it.

svg/altGlyphDef.name: altGlyphDef
svg/altGlyphDef.summary: The `<altGlyphDef>` SVG element defines a substitution representation for glyphs.

svg/altGlyphItem.name: altGlyphItem
svg/altGlyphItem.summary: The `<altGlyphItem>` element provides a set of candidates for glyph substitution by the altGlyph element.

svg/animate.name: animate
svg/animate.summary: The SVG `<animate>` element provides a way to animate an attribute of an element over time.

svg/animateMotion.name: animateMotion
svg/animateMotion.summary: The SVG `<animateMotion>` element provides a way to define how an element moves along a motion path.

keyPoints.name: keyPoints
keyPoints.summary: The `keyPoints` attribute indicates the simple duration of an animation.

path.name: path
path.summary: The `path` attribute has two different meanings, either it defines a text path along which the characters of a text are rendered, or a motion path along which a referenced element is animated.

rotate.name: rotate
rotate.summary: The `rotate` attribute specifies how the animated element rotates as it travels along a path specified in an animateMotion element.

svg/animateTransform.name: animateTransform
svg/animateTransform.summary: The `animateTransform` element animates a transformation attribute on its target element, thereby allowing animations to control translation, scaling, rotation, and/or skewing.

svg/circle.name: circle
svg/circle.summary: The `<circle>` SVG element is an SVG basic shape, used to draw circles based on a center point and a radius.

cx.name: cx
cx.summary: The `cx` attribute define the x-axis coordinate of a center point.

cy.name: cy
cy.summary: The `cy` attribute define the y-axis coordinate of a center point.

r.name: r
r.summary: The `r` attribute defines the radius of a circle.

pathLength.name: pathLength
pathLength.summary: The `pathLength` attribute lets authors specify a total length for the path, in user units. This value is then used to calibrate the browser's distance calculations with those of the author, by scaling all distance computations using the ratio `pathLength`/(computed value of path length).

svg/clipPath.name: clipPath
svg/clipPath.summary: The `<clipPath>` SVG element defines a clipping path, to be used by the clip-path property.

clipPathUnits.name: clipPathUnits
clipPathUnits.summary: The `clipPathUnits` attribute indicates which coordinate system to use for the contents of the clipPath element.

svg/cursor.name: cursor
svg/cursor.summary: Note: The CSS cursor property should be used instead of this element.

svg/defs.name: defs
svg/defs.summary: The `<defs>` element is used to store graphical objects that will be used at a later time. Objects created inside a `<defs>` element are not rendered directly. To display them you have to reference them (with a use element for example).

svg/desc.name: desc
svg/desc.summary: The `<desc>` element provides an accessible, long-text description of any SVG container element or graphics element.

svg/discard.name: discard
svg/discard.summary: The `<discard>` SVG element allows authors to specify the time at which particular elements are to be discarded, thereby reducing the resources required by an SVG user agent. This is particularly useful to help SVG viewers conserve memory while displaying long-running documents.

svg/ellipse.name: ellipse
svg/ellipse.summary: The `<ellipse>` element is an SVG basic shape, used to create ellipses based on a center coordinate, and both their x and y radius.

cx.name: cx
cx.summary: The `cx` attribute define the x-axis coordinate of a center point.

cy.name: cy
cy.summary: The `cy` attribute define the y-axis coordinate of a center point.

rx.name: rx
rx.summary: The `rx` attribute defines a radius on the x-axis.

ry.name: ry
ry.summary: The `ry` attribute defines a radius on the y-axis.

pathLength.name: pathLength
pathLength.summary: The `pathLength` attribute lets authors specify a total length for the path, in user units. This value is then used to calibrate the browser's distance calculations with those of the author, by scaling all distance computations using the ratio `pathLength`/(computed value of path length).

svg/feBlend.name: feBlend
svg/feBlend.summary: The `<feBlend>` SVG filter primitive composes two objects together ruled by a certain blending mode. This is similar to what is known from image editing software when blending two layers. The mode is defined by the mode attribute.

svg/feColorMatrix.name: feColorMatrix
svg/feColorMatrix.summary: The `<feColorMatrix>` SVG filter element changes colors based on a transformation matrix. Every pixel's color value `[R,G,B,A]` is matrix multiplied by a 5 by 5 color matrix to create new color `[R',G',B',A']`.

svg/feComponentTransfer.name: feComponentTransfer
svg/feComponentTransfer.summary: The `<feComponentTransfer>` SVG filter primitive performs color-component-wise remapping of data for each pixel. It allows operations like brightness adjustment, contrast adjustment, color balance or thresholding.

svg/feComposite.name: feComposite
svg/feComposite.summary: The `<feComposite>` SVG filter primitive performs the combination of two input images pixel-wise in image space using one of the Porter-Duff compositing operations: `over`, `in`, `atop`, `out`, `xor`, `lighter`, or `arithmetic`.

svg/feConvolveMatrix.name: feConvolveMatrix
svg/feConvolveMatrix.summary: The `<feConvolveMatrix>` SVG filter primitive applies a matrix convolution filter effect. A convolution combines pixels in the input image with neighboring pixels to produce a resulting image. A wide variety of imaging operations can be achieved through convolutions, including blurring, edge detection, sharpening, embossing and beveling.

svg/feDiffuseLighting.name: feDiffuseLighting
svg/feDiffuseLighting.summary: The `<feDiffuseLighting>` SVG filter primitive lights an image using the alpha channel as a bump map. The resulting image, which is an RGBA opaque image, depends on the light color, light position and surface geometry of the input bump map.

svg/feDisplacementMap.name: feDisplacementMap
svg/feDisplacementMap.summary: The `<feDisplacementMap>` SVG filter primitive uses the pixel values from the image from in2 to spatially displace the image from in.

svg/feDistantLight.name: feDistantLight
svg/feDistantLight.summary: The `<feDistantLight>` filter primitive defines a distant light source that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.

svg/feDropShadow.name: feDropShadow
svg/feDropShadow.summary: The SVG `<feDropShadow>` filter primitive creates a drop shadow of the input image. It can only be used inside a  element.

dx.name: dx
dx.summary: The `dx` attribute indicates a shift along the x-axis on the position of an element or its content.

dy.name: dy
dy.summary: The `dy` attribute indicates a shift along the y-axis on the position of an element or its content.

stdDeviation.name: stdDeviation
stdDeviation.summary: The `stdDeviation` attribute defines the standard deviation for the blur operation.

svg/feFlood.name: feFlood
svg/feFlood.summary: The `<feFlood>` SVG filter primitive fills the filter subregion with the color and opacity defined by flood-color and flood-opacity.

svg/feFuncA.name: feFuncA
svg/feFuncA.summary: The `<feFuncA>` SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the alpha component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.

svg/feFuncB.name: feFuncB
svg/feFuncB.summary: The `<feFuncB>` SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the blue component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.

svg/feFuncG.name: feFuncG
svg/feFuncG.summary: The `<feFuncG>` SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the green component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.

svg/feFuncR.name: feFuncR
svg/feFuncR.summary: The `<feFuncR>` SVG filter primitive defines the transfer function for the red component of the input graphic of its parent feComponentTransfer element.

svg/feGaussianBlur.name: feGaussianBlur
svg/feGaussianBlur.summary: The `<feGaussianBlur>` SVG filter primitive blurs the input image by the amount specified in stdDeviation, which defines the bell-curve.

svg/feImage.name: feImage
svg/feImage.summary: The `<feImage>` SVG filter primitive fetches image data from an external source and provides the pixel data as output (meaning if the external source is an SVG image, it is rasterized.)

svg/feMerge.name: feMerge
svg/feMerge.summary: The `<feMerge>` SVG element allows filter effects to be applied concurrently instead of sequentially. This is achieved by other filters storing their output via the result attribute and then accessing it in a feMergeNode child.

svg/feMergeNode.name: feMergeNode
svg/feMergeNode.summary: The `feMergeNode` takes the result of another filter to be processed by its parent feMerge.

svg/feMorphology.name: feMorphology
svg/feMorphology.summary: The `<feMorphology>` SVG filter primitive is used to erode or dilate the input image. Its usefulness lies especially in fattening or thinning effects.

svg/feOffset.name: feOffset
svg/feOffset.summary: The `<feOffset>` SVG filter primitive allows to offset the input image. The input image as a whole is offset by the values specified in the dx and dy attributes.

svg/fePointLight.name: fePointLight
svg/fePointLight.summary: The `<fePointLight>` filter primitive defines a light source which allows to create a point light effect. It that can be used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.

svg/feSpecularLighting.name: feSpecularLighting
svg/feSpecularLighting.summary: The `<feSpecularLighting>` SVG filter primitive lights a source graphic using the alpha channel as a bump map. The resulting image is an RGBA image based on the light color. The lighting calculation follows the standard specular component of the Phong lighting model. The resulting image depends on the light color, light position and surface geometry of the input bump map. The result of the lighting calculation is added. The filter primitive assumes that the viewer is at infinity in the z direction.

svg/feSpotLight.name: feSpotLight
svg/feSpotLight.summary: The `<feSpotLight>` SVG filter primitive defines a light source that can be used to create a spotlight effect. It is used within a lighting filter primitive: feDiffuseLighting or feSpecularLighting.

svg/feTile.name: feTile
svg/feTile.summary: The `<feTile>` SVG filter primitive allows to fill a target rectangle with a repeated, tiled pattern of an input image. The effect is similar to the one of a pattern.

svg/feTurbulence.name: feTurbulence
svg/feTurbulence.summary: The `<feTurbulence>` SVG filter primitive creates an image using the Perlin turbulence function. It allows the synthesis of artificial textures like clouds or marble. The resulting image will fill the entire filter primitive subregion.

svg/filter.name: filter
svg/filter.summary: The `<filter>` SVG element defines a custom filter effect by grouping atomic filter primitives. It is never rendered itself, but must be used by the filter attribute on SVG elements, or the filter CSS property for SVG/HTML elements.

svg/font.name: font
svg/font.summary: The `<font>` SVG element defines a font to be used for text layout.

svg/font-face.name: font-face
svg/font-face.summary: The `<font-face>` SVG element corresponds to the CSS @font-face rule. It defines a font's outer properties.

svg/font-face-format.name: font-face-format
svg/font-face-format.summary: The `<font-face-format>` SVG element describes the type of font referenced by its parent font-face-uri.

svg/font-face-name.name: font-face-name
svg/font-face-name.summary: The `<font-face-name>` element points to a locally installed copy of this font, identified by its name.

svg/font-face-src.name: font-face-src
svg/font-face-src.summary: The `<font-face-src>` SVG element corresponds to the @font-face/src descriptor in CSS @font-face rules. It serves as container for font-face-name, pointing to locally installed copies of this font, and font-face-uri, utilizing remotely defined fonts.

svg/font-face-uri.name: font-face-uri
svg/font-face-uri.summary: The `<font-face-uri>` SVG element points to a remote definition of the current font.

svg/foreignObject.name: foreignObject
svg/foreignObject.summary: The `<foreignObject>` SVG element includes elements from a different XML namespace. In the context of a browser, it is most likely (X)HTML.

height.name: height
height.summary: The `height` attribute defines the vertical length of an element in the user coordinate system.

width.name: width
width.summary: The `width` attribute defines the horizontal length of an element in the user coordinate system.

x.name: x
x.summary: The `x` attribute defines an x-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.

y.name: y
y.summary: The `y` attribute defines a y-axis coordinate in the user coordinate system.

svg/g.name: g
svg/g.summary: The `<g>` SVG element is a container used to group other SVG elements.

svg/glyph.name: glyph
svg/glyph.summary: A `<glyph>` defines a single glyph in an SVG font.

svg/glyphRef.name: glyphRef
svg/glyphRef.summary: The `glyphRef` element provides a single possible glyph to the referencing altGlyph substitution.

svg/hkern.name: hkern
svg/hkern.summary: The `<hkern>` SVG element allows to fine-tweak the horizontal distance between two glyphs. This process is known as kerning.

svg/image.name: image
svg/image.summary: The `<image>` SVG element includes images inside SVG documents. It can display raster image files or other SVG files.

svg/line.name: line
svg/line.summary: The `<line>` element is an SVG basic shape used to create a line connecting two points.

x1.name: x1
